    <stitle>HUBS, BEARINGS, AND SEALS (NON-DRIVE AXLES) - HUB ASSEMBLY</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>HUB ASSEMBLY</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="inspect" graphiccount="7">
            <title>CLEAN AND INSPECT</title>
            <para>Clean hub with mineral solvent and air pressure dry. Check assembly for:</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Worn Stud Holes (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0200235">Figure 35</hotlnk>). This condition is caused by stud turning in the hole
                    because of insufficient torque on the inner nut (stud). Replace hub.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0200235" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg02/G0200235.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="208px"
                             scalefitheight="232px" resolution="150"/>
                    <caption>Figure 35. Worn Stud Holes</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Worn Mounting Face (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0200236">Figure 36</hotlnk>). This condition is caused by a loose wheel assembly
                    with outboard mounted drum. The outer mounting face of the brake drum is worn. Replace hub or brake
                    drum.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0200236" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg02/G0200236.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="208px"
                             scalefitheight="232px" resolution="150"/>
                    <caption>Figure 36. Worn Mounting Face</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Broken or Stripped Threads Wheel Stud (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0200237">Figure 37</hotlnk>
                    and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0200238">Figure 38</hotlnk>). Replace studs.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0200237" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg02/G0200237.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                             scalefitheight="232px" resolution="150"/>
                    <caption>Figure 37. Broken Studs</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f0200238" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg02/G0200238.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="272px" resolution="150"/>
                    <caption>Figure 38. Stripped Threads</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Porous Condition Where Leakage May Occur. Replace hub.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Bent Hub Face (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0200239">Figure 39</hotlnk>). This condition can be caused by wheels running loose
                    for an extended period of time. Continual retightening of wheel nuts is an indication of bent hub;
                    hub should be checked. If there is more than a 1/32 inch gap as shown in
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0200239">Figure 39</hotlnk>
                    , replace hub.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0200239" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg02/G0200239.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="208px"
                             scalefitheight="272px" resolution="150"/>
                    <caption>Figure 39. Bent Hub Face</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. STRAIGHT EDGE</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. HUB</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. GAP BETWEEN HUB FACE AND STRAIGHT EDGE</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Abused Hub (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0200240">Figure 40</hotlnk>). This condition is caused by overloading, improper
                    tire changes, hitting curbs at high speeds, or hitting curbs at sharp angles.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0200240" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg02/G0200240.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="272px" resolution="150"/>
                    <caption>Figure 40. Abused Hub</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Dirty hub. Clean aluminum hub with a wire brush (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0200241">Figure 41</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0200241" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg02/G0200241.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="232px" resolution="150"/>
                    <caption>Figure 41. Cleaning Aluminum Hub</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
